          "body": "Mephibosheth's response in 9:8 is one of the most theologically loaded self-descriptions in the Hebrew Bible: 'What is your servant, that you should regard a dead dog like me?' A dog was the most despised animal in ancient Israelite culture — not a pet but a scavenger, associated with dishonor and death. A 'dead dog' compounds the worthlessness: useless even for the work a living dog does. Mephibosheth is not feigning humility; he is making a precise self-assessment from within the world's categories. He is crippled, from a fallen house, a political liability, hidden in obscurity. By every natural measure, he is nothing. The chapter's entire power rests on this contrast: the man who calls himself a dead dog ends the chapter seated at the king's table as one of the king's sons. Grace does not confirm the self-assessment — it overrules it with a royal declaration. This is the structure of the gospel: the recipient contributes the wretchedness; the giver contributes the status."
