          "title": "The lame man at the table — grace without transformation of condition",
          "body": "The narrator's final sentence is deliberately restrained: 'Now he was lame in both feet' (9:13). After thirteen verses of restoration, the chapter closes with the reminder that Mephibosheth's physical condition has not changed. He did not walk into the palace; he was brought (9:5). He will eat at the table with his feet under it — hidden, perhaps, but lame. Commentators from Calvin to Keller have noted that this closing detail is the chapter's most important pastoral observation: grace does not always cure the condition that makes one helpless. It seats the uncured at the table. Mephibosheth eats every day with his disability intact, his lineage unchanged, his past unrevised — and he eats as one of the king's sons, permanently, by covenant. The grace is real precisely because it does not depend on his condition being fixed. For the reader who comes to this text carrying something unfixed in their own life, the narrator's final note is not a caveat but a comfort."
