        "body": "Having made the promise to Mephibosheth, David now turns to Ziba and creates the institutional apparatus that will make the promise self-sustaining. The gift of land without the means to work it would be a hollow gift — the restored estate of Saul was considerable, and Mephibosheth, crippled in both feet, cannot farm it himself. David therefore assigns Ziba, his fifteen sons, and his twenty servants as permanent agricultural servants to Mephibosheth's household. Thirty-six people are commissioned to ensure that one man has food.\n\nThe structure of verses 9-10 is significant. David says 'All that belonged to Saul and to all his house I have given to your master's grandson' — the perfect tense in Hebrew signals a completed royal decree, irreversible and formal. Then the imperative follows: 'you and your sons and your servants shall cultivate the land.' The decree precedes the command; the gift is real before the labor begins. This is the Old Testament pattern of gift preceding obligation — the same pattern as the Sinai covenant, where 'I am the LORD your God who brought you out of Egypt' precedes the commandments (Exodus 20:2).\n\nThe parenthetical note in verse 10 — 'Now Ziba had fifteen sons and twenty servants' — is not incidental. It is the narrator's way of showing the scale of the provision. One lame man, formerly hidden in Lo-debar, now has thirty-six people working his land. The provision wildly exceeds the minimum. This is the chapter's portrait of what divine-analog grace looks like: not barely sufficient, but abundantly structured.\n\nZiba's response in 9:11a is formally compliant — 'According to all that my lord the king commands his servant, so your servant will do' — but attentive readers will note that this is the language of an obedient subject, not a cheerful participant. Later in the narrative (2 Samuel 16:1-4; 19:24-30), Ziba will exploit the very arrangement established here, slandering Mephibosheth to David during Absalom's revolt. The narrator plants nothing explicit in 9:11, but the formal compliance is a thread to watch.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tamid* ('regularly,' 9:10) — the same word used in the Torah for the daily burnt offering (*olat tamid*, Exodus 29:42). The table-fellowship is structurally permanent, as much an institution of David's court as the sacrificial system is of Israel's worship. The repetition of *tamid* in 9:7, 10, and 13 creates a deliberate liturgical resonance."
