        "body": "The chapter's closing paragraph compresses fulfillment into three sentences. The narrator confirms that the promise has become daily reality: 'Mephibosheth ate at David's table as one of the king's sons' (9:11b). The comparison 'as one of the king's sons' is the highest status David could confer short of actual adoption. At the table of a Near Eastern king, the king's sons were the most honored guests — they received the choicest portions, sat in the place of greatest dignity, and shared the king's own provision. Mephibosheth is not a tolerated guest at a side table; he is seated with the princes.\n\nVerse 12 adds a genealogical detail — Mephibosheth had a young son named Mica — which serves a double purpose. First, it shows that Mephibosheth's own household will continue (the Saul-Jonathan line is not extinguished); second, it implies that the covenant chesed extends through another generation. The blessing given to Mephibosheth will descend to Mica just as the covenant with Jonathan descended to Mephibosheth. Genealogy is the Old Testament's way of tracking covenant continuity.\n\nVerse 13 is the chapter's closing statement, and the narrator composes it with deliberate craft: 'So Mephibosheth lived in Jerusalem, for he ate at the king's table regularly. Now he was lame in both feet.' The final clause — 'Now he was lame in both feet' — has generated significant interpretive discussion. Some read it as a closing biographical note with no theological weight. But the positioning argues otherwise: the narrator has been structuring this chapter toward the table, and having arrived there, he closes with the reminder of what did not change. Mephibosheth did not walk into Jerusalem; he was brought. He did not earn his place at the table; he received it. He did not cure his lameness; he sat down with it.\n\nThis is the chapter's final theological statement, and it is one of the Old Testament's most honest pastoral observations: grace seats the lame man at the royal table. It does not first make him capable of standing. The table-fellowship is real, permanent, daily, and lavish — and the man eating it is still crippled. For readers who carry uncured conditions into the presence of God, this is not a minor detail. It is the heart of the story.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pisseach* (lame, 9:13) differs from *nakheh* (stricken/crippled, 9:3) used at the chapter's opening — the narrator uses a different term at the close, but both describe the same physical condition. The bookending of the chapter with two different terms for lameness is the narrator's device for ensuring the reader cannot forget the condition that grace overrode."
